instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "According to ISO 26262-1, the Digital Twin of an Adaptive Cruise Control System must be categorized by ASIL depth based on systematic hazard analysis that assigns Severity (S), Exposure (E), and Controllability (C). The resulting ASIL dictates safety objectives, safety functions, and the required safety integrity levels for all vehicle-to-vehicle and vehicle-to-infrastructure (V2X) data exchanges. 3GPP TS 22.185 prescribes a security architecture for V2X communications, requiring mutual authentication via TLS-based key establishment, message confidentiality using 128-bit AES encryption, integrity protection using HMAC-SHA256, and pseudonym-based identity management to satisfy GDPR-like privacy constraints. The standard mandates a dynamic key-revocation mechanism and supports both DSRC (802.11p) and C-V2X (LTE-based) channels, with redundancy plans for cellular handover to mitigate communication loss. ISO 15622 provides test procedures that explicitly validate end-to-end latency of safety-critical messages (≤10 ms) and verifies that fail-safe states (e.g., transition to manual control) are triggered within the driver’s reaction time. In practice, the Digital Twin implements a watchdog that monitors sensor fusion loops; on detection of anomalous data, it triggers an emergency braking cascade, logs the fault, and on-board diagnostics report the event to external roadside units. Functional safety is integrated with cybersecurity by treating cybersecurity threats as hazards during the HARA, thus ensuring that safety-critical messages are protected against spoofing, tampering, and denial-of-service attacks."
]
